{You are North and it is your bid. Decide what you would say, then  on BID. 

With 12 points and an excellent suit you overcall 1\H.

Partner raises to 4\H and everyone passes.

North plays 4\H. East leads the \DA and the defense wins two high \Ds then switches to a trump.

Losers: \S 0 : \H 0 : \D 2 : \C 2 : Total = 4

The two \D losers are already lost, so you must eliminate a \C loser. If East has the \CK then a simple finesse will win the day. That would be a 50% chance, right? WRONG! That would be a 0% chance. You and partner hold 23 HCP. East has already produced 4 HCP with the \DA, and if he had 3 more that would mean West opened with only 10 points. Very doubtful.

So face it, West has the \CK.

However, dummy has some nice \S cards. So you pull the last trump, play your \S3 to dummy's \SA, then lead the \SQ. If West puts on his \SK (which you know he must have) you ruff it. Then enter dummy with a \D ruff and discard the small \C on the good \SJ. If West doesn't play his \SK you discard your  \C loser immediately.

This was a perfect example. After the opening lead it was easy to deduce that all the rest of the high cards had to be in the West hand.}
